	*3. City-level publication: "Financial Statistics of Cities"
	
	*************************************************************
	- Since act of Congress of 1898 (first report: 1899)
	- For cities with population over 30,000 (over 100,000 from 1932)
	- includes Assessed Valuation of Property, Basis of Assessment (until 1930), Taxes Levied, Tax Rate, and the Per Capita Assessed Valuation, Tax Levy, and Debt
LINKS:
- 1902 - 1938: https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/164
- 1932 - 1945: https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100122716
- 1939 - 1963: https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/002137361

Text for tables from 1907 include data for :
(i) city with two or more tax rates (for different parts of city or classes of property) 
(ii) special property taxes (mostly corporation and bank stock)
(iii) poll taxes from 1925 (likely presented in other sections in earlier reports)

Variables included in tables (1916)
- Assessed valuation of property
- Reported basis of assessment in practice (percent of estimated true value)
- Per capita assessment
- Rate of Levy (including poll tax)
- Levy (including poll tax)

NB: 
1. assessed valuation given for each division of city (city state, county, over division) as 
	i) tax base may differ 
	ii) for independent division of a city, a) areas of city may differ b) different tax base
	iii) special case: 
"The figures on a line for one of the divisions of the government of a city represent the assessed valuation of the
property located within the limits of the city corporation subject to taxation for the maintenance of such
division, as appraised at the assessment made for the  purpose of such division, whether it is the same as or
different from that made for city corporation purposes, except those for divisions of which less than 10 per
cent of the valuation was outside the limits of the city corporation."

2. Definition of general property tax and special property tax
"General property taxes are direct taxes levied upon property in general, in proportion to its assessed or appraised value. 
Under this head are included all property taxes whose assessment and collection are by methods substantially identical
 with those employed in the taxation of the property of the average citizen. Special property taxes are direct taxes 
levied or collected, or levied and collected, by methods not applied to property in general. Among such taxes are those 
popularly referred to as corporation taxes, bank taxes, security taxes, mortgage taxes, frontage taxes, tonnage taxes, 
merchants' taxes, manufacturers' taxes, etc.� Report 1902 p12

